Inferences and monotonocity

  • people make inferences like the following:

More than half of the tourist have the flu.

\(\rightarrow\) More than half of the tourists are sick.

All tourists have the flu.

\(\rightarrow\) All tourists are sick.

  • but only the second inference is valid in FOL

  • the complexity isnât psychologically detectable

  • Geurts and Slik (2005): monotonicity helps, it allows shallow and quick inferences: upward, downward, etc.

  • from this perspective: NPIs help to make inferences (clues of the downward monotonicity of the sentence)

  • Geurts and Slik (2005): not about NPIs but about some general rules of inference

  • one of their patterns:

\(\uparrow\)Det\(_A\) \(\uparrow\)Det\(_B\) < \(\downarrow\)Det\(_A\) \(\downarrow\)Det\(_B\) < {\(\uparrow\)Det\(_A\) \(\downarrow\)Det\(_B\), \(\downarrow\)Det\(_A\) \(\uparrow\)Det\(_B\)}

  • Geurts and Slik (2005): experiment on syllogisms

Det\(_A\) A played against Det\(_B\) B. (major promise)

All B were C. (minor promise)

Det\(_A\) A played against Det\(_B\) C. (conclusion)

  • Det\(_A\): âeveryâ, âmostâ, âsomeâ, âat least 3â, âat most 3â, ânoâ

  • Det\(_B\): âmore than 2â or âfewer than 2â.

  • A, B, C: substantives like âforesterâ, ânurseâ, âsocialist

Series of experiments

Szabolcsi, Bott, and McElree (2008)

  • first negative results

  • example item from the main experiment:

  • DE: \(p \rightarrow (p \vee q)\)
  • the expectation was that the NPI would facilitate the DE inference
  • generally: DE and UE operators, NPI or not below them
  • the results:

  • \(\neg((p \vee q) \rightarrow \neg p)\) is valid

  • the material is slightly questionable but the experiment is well designed

  • the authors comment on the results as follows: âGiven the existing evidence on NPI licensing, it seems almost like a foregone conclusion that the processor should recognize the relationship between monotonicity and NPI licensing. Indeed, when we started this project, our intention was to investigate how this recognition occurred, rather than whether it occurred. As is often the case, however, expectations did not match results and we were unable to find evidence for the recognition.â

Chemla, Homer, and Rothschild (2011)

  • batch of experiments looking at monotonicity, scalar implicatures and NPIs
  • the NPI and monotonicity part are the following:

no-NPI: Chaque alien qui a de lâintÃ©ret pour la littÃ©rature est rouge.

Every alien who takes an interest in literature is red.

NPI: Chaque alien qui a le moindre intÃ©ret pour la littÃ©rature est rouge.

Every alien who takes any interest in literature is red.

  • French NPI le moindre (literally âthe leastâ) â very close to Czech sebemenÅ¡Ã­

  • monotonicity part:

Set: Chaque alien a fait de la danse.

Every Alien practiced dance.

Subset: Chaque alien a fait de la danse classique.

Every Alien practiced classical dance.

  • quantifiers varied (downward, upward, non-monotonic): no, some, every, less than 12, at most 12, exactly 12, only 12

  • the results: the inferences a particular person considers valid in a given linguistic environment predict how acceptable they would find an NPI in that same environment

  • first positive result

  • the method: correlation between the (by speaker) acceptance of NPI and her monotonicity judgments

  • but the correlation worked only in case both PPI and NPI results were aggregated

DeniÄ et al. (2021)

  • again experiment on NPIs and reasoning
  • they start with an assumption: in cases where reasoning is easy, adding NPIs doesnât make a difference (as in Szabolcsi, Bott, and McElree (2008))
  • first environment: non-monotonic quantifiers (the crucial condition)

Exactly 12 aliens saw (some/any) birds.

Exactly 12 aliens saw doves.

  • the effect is very small and significant only in experiment 2 (both premise and conclusion contani PIs)

  • but in UE reasoning, presence of NPIs makes a difference

  • examples like:

Exactly 12 aliens saw any doves.

Exactly 12 aliens saw any birds.

  • presence of NPI makes the inference less acceptable: âwith inferences without PI and with a PPI receiving similar directional ratings (59.2%, SD = 14.9 and 60.1%, SD = 14.1, respectively), and the presence of NPIs leading to lower ratings (54.7%, SD = 12.5)â

  • second environment: double DE

  • every and no, subset, superset

Every alien who did not see (some/any) doves is hairy.

Every alien who did not see birds is hairy.

No alien spent a year without seeing (some/any) doves.

No alien spent a year without seeing birds.

  • âno effect of the presence of NPIs on the global monotonicity inference was found, but interestingly, an effect of the PPI was foundâ
  • in experiment 4 they found some effect even with NPIs

Interim summary

  • the effects of NPIs/PPIs are either non-detectable or very small

Locality and NPIs: Mayer, Wurmbrand, and Sprouse (2019)

  • experimental evidence for the flip-flop effect:

The scope theory?

  • what if Szabolcsi, Bott, and McElree (2008) was right (also the magnitude of effects in DeniÄ et al. (2021) and others is nearly anecdotal)
  • DE doesnât work for non-monotonic quantifiers anyway
